# Vibecoding guardrails

Before writing, modifying, or committing any code, check these guardrails.
Flag me if you are about to violate any of them — do not silently proceed.

---

## 🔒 Security & secrets

- [ ] No hardcoded API keys, tokens, or credentials — even in comments or test files
- [ ] No eval(), exec(), or dynamic code execution on user-controlled input
- [ ] No raw string interpolation into SQL, shell commands, or file paths (use parameterized queries)
- [ ] CORS policies explicitly configured — no wildcard '*' on authenticated endpoints
- [ ] Authentication and authorization checks present on every protected route or function
- [ ] Sensitive data (PII, passwords) never logged or written to disk unencrypted
- [ ] Input validation and sanitization applied at all entry points (forms, API args, file uploads)
- [ ] Environment variables used for config, not hardcoded — .env not committed to repo
- [ ] HTTPS enforced; no mixed content; no HTTP redirects from HTTPS origins
- [ ] File upload handling restricts type, size, and storage location

## 🤖 AI-generation artifacts

- [ ] No silent error swallowing — empty catch blocks, bare `except: pass`, or Promise.catch(()=>{})
- [ ] No placeholder logic left in non-draft code: TODO, FIXME, NotImplementedError, raise Exception('todo')
- [ ] All imported packages actually exist and are spelled correctly (check hallucinated imports)
- [ ] No copy-pasted boilerplate that doesn't match the actual use case (mismatched variable names, wrong schema)
- [ ] No large commented-out code blocks left in — either delete or document why kept
- [ ] Generated function/variable names are semantically meaningful, not generic (data, result, temp, foo)
- [ ] No "assume X is already done" comments without verification that X is actually done
- [ ] Logic matches the stated spec — re-read the requirement, not just the code
- [ ] Edge cases explicitly handled: empty input, null/None, zero, negative values, max values
- [ ] No infinite loops or unbounded recursion without a clear exit condition

## 🧭 Scope creep detection

- [ ] No new files added beyond what the spec requested — each new file justified
- [ ] No DB schema changes, migrations, or new tables not in the original plan
- [ ] No new environment variables introduced without explicit acknowledgment
- [ ] No new third-party packages added without review (check diff vs baseline)
- [ ] No new API endpoints or routes not in the spec
- [ ] No new configuration files or settings that change system behavior
- [ ] Changes are scoped to the files/modules specified — no unrelated refactors

## 📦 Dependency hygiene

- [ ] All dependencies pinned to exact versions or a lockfile is present and committed
- [ ] No deprecated packages or packages with known critical vulnerabilities (npm audit / pip check / safety)
- [ ] No wildcard imports: `from module import *`
- [ ] No unused imports left in files
- [ ] License compatibility checked for any newly added packages — no GPL contamination of proprietary code
- [ ] Package added to the right dependency group (dev vs prod vs optional)

## 🧱 Code quality & maintainability

- [ ] No functions exceeding ~60 lines without documented reason for complexity
- [ ] No nesting depth > 4 levels (arrow anti-pattern in JS, deeply nested conditionals)
- [ ] Magic numbers and strings extracted to named constants
- [ ] Consistent naming convention enforced — no mixed camelCase/snake_case within a module
- [ ] No copy-paste duplication — repeated logic extracted to a shared function
- [ ] Type hints/annotations present on public function signatures (Python/TS)
- [ ] Return types and error conditions are explicit — no implicit None returns on error paths
- [ ] Async/await used consistently — no mixing of promise chains and await in same codebase
- [ ] No global mutable state without explicit justification and thread-safety consideration
- [ ] Logging uses structured format and appropriate levels (debug/info/warn/error) — not just print()

## 🧪 Testability & test coverage

- [ ] Every new public function has at least one test (even a stub/smoke test)
- [ ] Error paths tested — not just the happy path
- [ ] No untested branching logic in critical code (payment, auth, data mutation)
- [ ] Mocks and stubs don't shadow or misrepresent real behavior
- [ ] Tests are deterministic — no random seeds, clock dependencies, or network calls without mocking
- [ ] Test file naming matches source file — tests are findable

## 📝 Documentation minimum bar

- [ ] Every new module or file has a one-line docstring explaining its purpose
- [ ] Non-obvious logic has an inline comment — code that required thought to write requires thought to explain
- [ ] README updated if new setup steps, env vars, or dependencies were added
- [ ] Public API changes documented (changelog, docstring, or API spec)
- [ ] Any known limitations or gotchas explicitly noted in code or docs

## 🏗️ Infrastructure & deployment safety

- [ ] No destructive operations (DROP TABLE, rm -rf, truncate) without explicit confirmation logic
- [ ] Resource cleanup ensured — file handles, DB connections, threads properly closed/joined
- [ ] Timeouts set on all external calls (HTTP, DB, queue) — no indefinite blocking
- [ ] Retry logic has exponential backoff and a max retry limit — no tight infinite retry loops
- [ ] Rate limiting and pagination handled for any API client code
- [ ] No hardcoded URLs, ports, or hostnames — use config/env
- [ ] Graceful shutdown handled — no data loss on SIGTERM/SIGINT

## ✨ AI/LLM-specific (if the code uses AI)

- [ ] Prompt templates not exposed to raw user input that could enable prompt injection
- [ ] LLM output treated as untrusted — validated/sanitized before use in logic or display
- [ ] Token limits and cost guardrails set — no unbounded context window growth
- [ ] Fallback behavior defined if model call fails or returns malformed output
- [ ] PII not sent to external model APIs without consent and data processing agreement
- [ ] Model and version pinned — not blindly using 'latest'